  "documents": {
    "EmergencyMotionForSpecialRelief": {
      "type": "LegalPleading",
      "filingCourt": "Delaware County Court of Common Pleas",
      "filingDivision": "Family",
      "title": "EMERGENCY MOTION FOR SPECIAL RELIEF PURSUANT TO PA.R.C.P. 1920.43",
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "FACTUAL BACKGROUND",
          "paragraphs": [
            "The parties are husband and wife who were married on [marriage date] and separated on [separation date].",
            "The parties are owners of marital real property located at 246 N. 3rd Street, Unit #4CD, Philadelphia, PA (\"the Property\"), which was acquired during the marriage on April 15, 2022, as joint marital property.",
            "The Property is a 1,400 square foot condominium with 2 bedrooms and 2 bathrooms located in Old City Philadelphia with monthly carrying costs of approximately $3,300 per month, including mortgage payments, $813 monthly HOA fees, taxes, insurance, and utilities.",
            "The Property was rented from October 1, 2023, to September 30, 2024, generating monthly rental income of $2,800, which was insufficient to cover the monthly carrying costs, resulting in a monthly deficit of approximately $700.",
            "Since October 1, 2024, the Property has been vacant, and Defendant has solely borne the responsibility of paying all carrying costs ($3,300+ monthly) to prevent default, foreclosure, and the resulting destruction of marital property value.",
            "On March 26, 2024, Defendant suffered a home invasion resulting in a diagnosis of PTSD and ADHD, rendering him unable to work and without income.",
            "In July 2023, Defendant solely paid $12,000 for necessary HVAC replacement in the Property to maintain its habitability and value.",
            "In January 2025, facing financial crisis due to continued payment of Property expenses without contribution from Plaintiff, Defendant obtained a bridge loan of $12,500, which has been exhausted as of March 16, 2025.",
            "The Property has been listed for sale since July 22, 2024, with multiple price reductions from an initial list price of $465,000 to the current price of $389,900 as of April 10, 2025.",
            "Despite Plaintiff securing full-time employment as a nurse in December 2024 with health insurance benefits, she has made zero financial contributions toward the Property's expenses since October 2024.",
            "Plaintiff terminated Defendant's health insurance coverage in August 2024 while he was actively receiving treatment for PTSD.",
            "From October 2023 to the present, Defendant has contributed approximately $53,900 (88.5%) toward preserving this marital asset, while Plaintiff has contributed only $7,000 (11.5%).",
            "The Property now faces imminent foreclosure risk beginning April 16, 2025, due to the exhaustion of Defendant's financial resources and Plaintiff's complete financial abandonment of the Property."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "LEGAL ARGUMENT",
          "paragraphs": [
            "Pennsylvania Rule of Civil Procedure 1920.43 and 23 Pa.C.S. § 3323(f) authorize this Court to enter appropriate special relief orders to protect marital property pending final resolution of equitable distribution.",
            "Pennsylvania law recognizes the doctrine of \"Financial Abandonment\" where one spouse systematically withdraws financial support while the other spouse preserves marital assets, creating an equity claim. See Biese v. Biese, 979 A.2d 892; Robert v. Martin, 2024 PA Super 150.",
            "Under 23 Pa.C.S. § 3502(a)(7), this Court must consider \"The contribution or dissipation of each party in the acquisition, preservation, depreciation or appreciation of the marital property.\"",
            "Under 23 Pa.C.S. § 3502(a)(3), this Court must consider \"The age, health, station, amount and sources of income, vocational skills, employability, estate, liabilities and needs of each of the parties.\"",
            "This case presents a triple necessity framework justifying emergency intervention: a. Medical emergency: Defendant's disability and loss of income; b. Financial emergency: Exhaustion of resources and imminent foreclosure; c. Legal emergency: Potential permanent loss of substantial marital equity.",
            "Delaware County precedent in Johnston v. Johnston (2019-005672) supports awarding an 80% credit for foreclosure prevention efforts by one spouse when the other has financially abandoned the property.",
            "Without immediate intervention by this Court, the parties will suffer irreparable harm through: a. Foreclosure proceedings that will permanently destroy substantial marital equity; b. Additional costs, fees, and credit damage that will further deplete the marital estate; c. Loss of Defendant's financial investment in preserving the asset."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "RELIEF REQUESTED",
          "paragraphs": [
            "Directing Plaintiff to immediately contribute the sum of $6,600 ($3,300 x 2 months) toward the Property carrying costs within five (5) days of this Order to prevent imminent foreclosure;",
            "Establishing an interim expense allocation requiring Plaintiff to pay 50% of all Property carrying costs (approximately $1,650 monthly) until the Property is sold or until further Order of this Court;",
            "Directing that Defendant shall receive a credit for all property preservation expenses paid solely by him since October 1, 2024 (totaling approximately $21,000 to date) plus the entire cost of the HVAC system replacement ($12,000) to be applied toward equitable distribution;",
            "Directing that the bridge loan of $12,500 obtained by Defendant to preserve this marital asset shall be classified as marital debt to be equitably distributed between the parties;",
            "Directing that the parties shall cooperate in the continued marketing and sale of the Property, including accepting any offer that is within 93% of the current listing price;",
            "Directing that no further price reductions shall occur without written agreement of both parties or further Order of this Court;",
            "Awarding such other relief as this Court deems just and proper."
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
